(187, NULL, NULL, 196, 'NA', 'Lead', 'gatereg@gmail.com', 'Kenya', '10888235', '7416-01000', 'Thika', 'Kenya', '0729534677', '<p>George G. Ndiritu PhD is a lecturer of the environment in Karatina University in Kenya and an environmental consultant specializing in wetlands and terrestrial studies. He has more than 20 years of experience in ecological research in wetlands and terrestrial biodiversity assessment and monitoring to support biodiversity management, including restoration and rehabilitation of ecosystems. His approach uses national and international standards including IFC Performance Standards and World Bank&rsquo;s operation policies for biodiversity assessment and conservation. He has built a strong career as an aquatic ecologist through carrying out wetland consultancies to support the sustainable management of wetlands in Kenya including the Global Biodiversity Assessment of Wetland Plants&rsquo; by IUCN for red listing species, NEMA&rsquo;s Wetland Monitoring and Assessment Strategy for Kenya by DANIDA and the development of Aquatic Ecosystem Monitoring Plan for Upper Tana Catchment by The Nature Conservancy (TNC). In addition, he was an ESIA lead expert in the 18MW Nyamindi Hydropower Cascade Project in Kirinyaga and a marine expert in the Lamu Coal Power Project. He was an ecologist in the Baseline Survey for Biodiversity in Transmara Forest Block (Mau Forest Complex), Forest Action Network (FAN), and The Economics Of Ecosystems And Biodiversity (TEEB) by International Climate Initiative (IKI)/National Museums of Kenya</p>\r\n<p>George has participated in many ecological terrestrial and wetlands studies in the country that has enabled him to publish more than twenty articles in peer-reviewed journals in almost all taxonomic groups for both aquatic and terrestrial environments. Also, he has published several technical reports and articles on biodiversity conservation. He is an active member of several Scientific Forums including the USA&rsquo;s Society of Freshwater Science (SFS) in which he attends the Society&rsquo;s meetings. He has reviewed articles for several journals and technical assessment reports (e.g. IPCC) on wetland, environment, taxonomy, biodiversity and climate change.</p>\r\n<p>As a staff of Karatina University, he is the Head of, the Department of Environmental Studies and some of the duties are supervising staff, mentoring both postgraduate and undergraduate students. He has tremendous organizational and leadership skills. He has travelled widely in Kenya and has excellent knowledge of the geographical social, cultural, political and physical settings of the country.</p>'),
