(1804, NULL, NULL, 1970, 'A005713595H', 'Lead', 'ysalah@worldbank.org', 'Kenyan', '22638302', 'P.O Box 15403', 'Nairobi', 'Nairobi Area', '0720318056', '<p>Yasin is climate change and environmental expert. Currently he is a consultant with World Bank Devolution and Locally-Led Climate Change Adaptation and Disaster Risk Management project. He has previously worked as &nbsp;Senior Disaster Risk Management and Resilience Officer at IFRC Regional Office in Nairobi and as Senior Programme Officer at IUCN People and Landscapes programme, Eastern and Southern Africa Regional Office where he actively led development and implementation of projects with objectives of strengthening the resilience of communities and ecosystems through improving understanding of the value of ecosystems and building requisite capacity of &nbsp;communities in sustainable natural resource, climate change adaptation&nbsp; and disaster risk management. He also worked as consultant at Camco Advisory Services (K) Ltd, researcher and teaching assistant at school of animal, plant and environmental science and forced migrations studies programme at University of the Witwatersrand Johannesburg, South Africa and trainee forester at Timboroa Forest Station Eldoret Kenya.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Yasin has over 10 years experience in climate change adaptation and mitigation, disaster risk management drought resilience, natural resource management, sustainable land management, green investments, environmental impact assessment, geographic information system and remote sensing, research and statistical analysis using various statistical packages.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Among the projects he designed and implemented previously includes building drought resilience through land and water management in selected catchments in Kenya and Uganda, Strengthening Hunger Resilience for Most vulnerable people in selected landscapes in Kenya and Somalia, Disaster Risk Reduction and Resilience in Somaliland and Puntland, Integrated approach in enhancing socio-economic and ecological resilience in Marsabit County Kenya, undertaking situational analysis on the state of climate change adaptation and mitigation&nbsp; efforts for agriculture in East Africa, climate risk assessment of Kenya&rsquo;s agricultural, water and energy sectors,&nbsp; preparation of East African Community Climate Change Master plan in particular element related to trans-boundary issues touching on the livelihood of the pastoralist communities and climate change dynamics among the East African member countries, REDD+ project in Imbirikani Group ranch in Kenya, Forest Restoration through Afforestation and Reforestation in Imbirikani Group Ranch, capacity building of the Tanzanian government employees in Ministry of Natural Resources and Tourism, Forestry and Bee Keeping Division on climate change and REDD+, feasibility study for deriving carbon finance from REDD+ project Kirisia forest reserve and Enderit Block of Mau Forest complex and developing sustainable charcoal Project Identification Form (PIF) and Project Preparatory Grant for UNDP (GEF) Tanzania. Yasin holds an MSc in environmental science from the University of the Witwatersrand and BSc in Forestry, Moi University</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Yasin was also involved in investigating the role of non-timber forest products in pastoralists/agro-pastoralists livelihood security and climate change adaptation in Garba Tula landscape of Northern Kenya a postmasters fellowship research in collaboration with Future Agricultures Consortium based at Institute of Development Studies (IDS), University of Sussex, Brighton UK. Yasin has published extensively and presented his research findings in many international conferences notably Third International Climate Change Adaptation, conference on the future of the agrifood sector in Africa, Accra, Ghana; International Geosphere-Biosphere Programme, Analysis, Integration and Modelling of the Earth System (AIMES) open science conference in Edinburgh and 5th EGU Alexander von Humboldt in Cape Town. He is a member of African Network of Earth System Scientists, IUCN Commission on Ecosystem management, Kenya Forest Working Group, IUCN expert team on Environment and Social Management system and South African Earth Observation Network.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Key Strengths</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Mainstreaming climate change into development initiatives including development of the relevant policies and climate finance</li>\r\n<li>Working with communities in drylands to build their resilience to drought and benefits from exploitation of natural resources sustainably</li>\r\n<li>Disaster risk management using integrated approach</li>\r\n<li>Climate change adaptation and mitigation in agriculture and natural resource sector&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>Biodiversity conservation and mainstreaming in various landscapes including arable, agro-pastoral and pastoral systems</li>\r\n<li>Environmental and social impact assessment</li>\r\n<li>Integration of the resilience and emergency operations</li>\r\n<li>Natural resource governance in pastoral and agro-pastoralist set-up</li>\r\n<li>Forest landscape restoration and carbon assessment</li>\r\n<li>GIS and remote sensing applications for natural resource management and development</li>\r\n</ul>'),
