(5242, NULL, NULL, 5640, NULL, 'Lead', 'x', 'Kenyan', '26321290', 'P.O Box 23', 'Msambweni', 'Kwale', '725210608', '<p>Dr Robert Runya is an interdisciplinary marine scientist with expertise spanning multiple domains, including environmental science, natural resources management, marine biology, oceanography, integrated coastal zone management, ocean acoustics, GIS &amp; Remote Sensing, statistical modelling, and has over 10 years of scientific research, marine conservation and programmes management experience at local and international levels. More recently, Robert has focused his research efforts at Ulster University (UK), where he pursued his PhD and developed methods based on remote sensing data for interrogating ecological questions of spatial nature, particularly related to species-habitat associations. One of his notable contributions includes pioneering research on the potential value of multi-frequency multibeam backscatter data to predict seafloor sediments and species distribution, which have garnered attention from the wider scientific community. Through his unwavering commitment and expertise, he continues to make significant strides in supporting efforts to develop best practices for monitoring, marine spatial planning and management of marine environment.</p>\r\n<p>Currently, Robert works as a Research Fellow at the Marine Institute in Ireland where he is involved in developing a spatial/planning scenarios<span>&nbsp;to identify mutually acceptable locations for Offshore Renewable Energy (ORE) projects and protected marine sites in the Celtic Sea, which minimize the displacement effect on fisheries.&nbsp;</span>Outside of his professional pursuits, Robert enjoys spending quality time with friends, exploring new destinations, indulging in movies and books, and discovering diverse cuisines. This well-rounded approach to life allows me to bring a unique perspective and understanding to the challenges and opportunities faced by young graduates.</p>'),
